metadata.name: Sand Shapes #83
metadata.description:
An experiment in line texture by Nate Donato, this piece features lines composed of a sand-like particle texture.  Bounds around line generation properties were set loosely, resulting in many possible line characters with unique weights, wobbles, and more.  Lines are generated in individual layered segments one by one, resulting in a pleasing animation of gradual composition as they compose one of twelve possible shapes, in one of eight possible color schemes.  

Each "line" is made up of thousands of points, and so rendering the live view of this piece may be computer intensive.  As an added bonus a small amount of proprietary line data is emitted to the development console, allowing the minted collection to serve as a palette of potential line qualities for the artist to use in future works.  Any owners of pieces used in this way by the artist on future projects will be granted a share of said future project's royalties.

In active live view, press [1] to view medium res, [2] to view high res, and [0] to return to original viewport width view.

Written in vanilla JavaScript without the use of external libraries.

metadata.name: Rococo #318
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 150 · 100 · 70 · 50 · 40 · 35 every 8 minutes. Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Nature’s wild flourish and untamed growth wondrously represent the exacting function of beauty — a function that is at once useful and infinitely creative. Perhaps nowhere is this delicate symbiosis better observed than in the flower, wherein a pure balance of physical fundamentals exists beneath ornate patterns and elaborate aesthetics.

Amongst the layers of undulating, vividly colored petals, attention-grabbing stigma and stamen, and lusciously decorative features, nature’s organic abundance and disorder disguises its masterful propensity for precision. Each of the flower’s components evolve through unpredictable interactions with an unwieldy natural environment, creating spectacular adaptations that emerge from the tension between what attracts.

Rococo painters appreciated the organic fluidity found in flowers and vegetal forms, using their joyful abundance to depict a break from the rigid and stoic period the artists hoped to leave behind. They sought to reframe perfection away from predictability and toward compositions as surprising as the natural world around them.

Thus, ‘Rococo’ is a generative distortion of an old tradition: a digital painting created entirely with code that interprets and processes the natural world’s dichotomies. This painting algorithm builds upon natural structures while melding and moving their colors beyond form, growing randomly organic iterations that are as perfect as they are imperfect.

Created by Ori Ben-Shabat & Ronen Tanchum @Phenomenalabs
Creative contributions from Tender @tender_art

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Technical Details:

- Mobile/GPU Intensive
- Press “s” to save a .png of the artwork in live view
- Press “p” to render a high res output + press “s” to save a printable .png

metadata.name: Smooth-brained #340
metadata.description:
A Generative Art Project by Matthew Hawtin & Murat Atimtay. Smooth-brained is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

The initial visual idea for ‘Smooth-brained’ was to use one pixel and a two-colour gradient in multiple ways across a grid, using repetition, orientation, placement and scale, resulting in a visual composition that became the genesis piece. From that original artwork, Murat took the premise and through creative-coding, began to expand and experiment on the parameters, introducing new visual possibilities and paving the way for this collaborative generative art collection. The beauty of a gradient is that it gives the impression of depth and form on a 2D surface. This allows the visual fields to seem outward and also inward while giving the impression of movement within the whole piece and within individual cells; conjuring up spaces within spaces. The compositions are meant to be spaces for the eye to roam, decorative yet functional, complex yet minimal, a place where the brain is pleased and not duly complicated - a state of ‘smooth-brained’.

Press 1 to 8 export PNG between 1000px to 8000px

metadata.name: EYES #179
metadata.description:
The beauty and soul of eyes have always fascinated me. There are billions of eyes in the world, all with different colors, textures and shapes and each one is still unique. With this project, I wanted to capture that natural beauty of the eyes, but also give them my unique colorful style.

Zombie and Cat eyes are more rare. Who will collect the Zombie Cat eye?

----

Created with the help of amazing cables.gl. For optimization purposes, in order to make the project load properly on fxhash, I had to use 2 textures for the eye pupil shapes instead of procedurally generating them. There is also hdr map loaded for the reflections.  

Press E to download the generated image.

----

All who collected NEBULAE were added to the reserve list. <3

metadata.name: an abstract concept #78
metadata.description:
I often try to duplicate my IRL analog abstract painting in code, and this, like my previous mint "a fleeting moment," is an attempt at that. Or it started that way. As is usual with such things, it quickly took on a life of its own. 

The algorithm itself consists of three layers of the main particle abstraction, which comes in five different styles, and roughly eight layers of the "texture," which comes in three styles. The palette consists of the background color and three colors for the particle algorithm. The texture is always drawn with the first of those three colors (the "base" color.) 

The result is indicative of my normal painting style (I almost always use three color layers over a background color, and paint with a spatula, palette knife, or cake knife) but is its own unique look.
